os homerseklete 26,7 Celsius fok. Delutan az atlaghomerseklet 30,8 fok. Hajnalban  23,9 fok. Altalaban december es januar - az eszak-keleti monszun ideje - a leghuvosebb honap. A relativ paratartalom ejjel gyakran tullepi a 90 szazalekot. Ugyanilyen paras a napkelte elotti hajnal.  Szaraz delutanokon a paratartalom 60 szazalekra csokken. A napi atlagos paratartalom 84,4 szazalek. A legtobb eso novemberben hull a szigetre es juliusban a legkevesebb. A leggyakrabban gyors es  hatalmas mennyisegu eso frissiti fel a levegot. Az evi csapadek mennyisege 23 355 millimeter.  Aprilisban es majusban, illetve oktoberben es novemberben gyakoriak a viharok. Az eddig mert  legnagyobb ereju szel elerte az orankenti 144 kilometeres sebesseget. Februar a legnaposabb honap, december pedig a legkevesbe napos. 1993. junius 30-an a Szingapurban allando lakhellyel rendelkezo nepesseg szama 2 873 800 volt, ket  szazalekkal tobb, mint 1992-ben es ennek kovetkezteben a nepsuruseg a negyzetkilometerkenti 3 893-rol  4 481-re nott. A kinaiak szamaranya 77,5, a malajoke 14,2, az indiaiake (fokent tamilok) 7,1, az egyeb etnikai  csoportokhoz tartozok aranya pedig 1,2 szazalek. A hivatalos nyelv az angol, malaj, kinai (mandarin) es a tamil. Malaj a nemzeti nyelv, mig az angol a  kormanyzas es a kozigazgatas nyelve. Az utcan tobbfele kinai es tamil dialektus hallhato. 1993-ban az irastudok aranya 91,6 szazalek volt. Az otthon is angolul beszelo csaladok aranyszama  folyamatosan novekszik es 1990-re elerte a 21 szazalekot, mig a kulonfele kinai dialektusokban beszelok  aranya tiz ev alatt 60 szazalekrol 38-ra (1990-es adat) csokkent. Szingapuri allampolgarsagot szuletessel, szarmazassal vagy bejelentkezessel lehet kapni. 1993-ban 11  296-an kerelmeztek allampolgarsagot. Ebbol osszesen 10 175-ot hagytak jova (beleertve a korabbi  evekben benyujtott kerelmeket). Az Orszagos Nyilvantarto Hivatal az allampolgaroknak es allando lakosoknak igazolvanyt ad. Az  allampolgarok rozsaszinu, az allando lakosok kek kartyat kapnak. Szingapur himnusza - Madzsula Szingapura - malaj nyelvu. Az allampolgarsag megszerzesekor a  kovetkezo eskut teszik: Mi, Szingapur allampolgarai fajtol, nyelvtol es vallastol fuggetlenul egyetlen es egyesult nepkent  kotelezzuk magunkat, hogy az igazsagra es egyenlosegre epulo, demokratikus tarsadalmat epitunk azert,  hogy nemzetunk szamara boldogsagot, joletet es haladast teremtsunk.==INTEGRACIO VAGY KISEMMIZES? (Havi Magyar Forum 1996. majus)A politikaban -- kulonosen a magyar politikaban -- nem ritka a fogalmakkal valo visszaeles. Raero politologusok egyszer talan majd azt is felmerik, hogy kozeletunkben melyik fogalommal tortenik a legtobb visszaeles. Valoszinu, hogy e dicstelen versenyben a DEMOKRACIA fogalma vinne el a palmat, de az is valoszinu, hogy a csucshoz kozeli helyezest erne el az utobbi evek divatos kozgazdasagi-politikai kifejezese: az INTEGRACIO.Nyugat-Europaban az integracio fogalma a hajdani Kozos Piac letrehozasakor kerult a kozforgalomba, es tobbe-kevesbe realisan fejezte ki a tagallamok torekveseit, hogy gazdasagukat osszekapcsoljak. Magyarorszagon 1990-tol kezdve emlegetjuk ezt a fogalmat. Eredetileg Magyarorszag es Nyugat-Europa szorosabb intezmenyesitett egyuttmukodeset volt hivatva kifejezni, de a liberalis politikai "establisment" ezt az ertelmezest hamarosan eltorzitotta, es az integracio kifejezes az o szohasznalatukban szinonim fogalom lett Magyarorszag altaluk propagalt EU-tagsagaval. Tehat amikor egy politikus Magyarorszag europai integraciojanak szuksegessegerol beszel, akkor azon valojaban azt erti, hogy Magyarorszagnak csatlakoznia kell az Europai Uniohoz.EZ A MEGTEVESZTO SZOHASZNALAT GYAKORI ESZKOZ A LIBERALISOK KEZEBEN A KODOSITESRE ES FELREVEZETESRE. Nem mas, mint egy olcso szemfenyvesztes, politikai trukk. Csak azt kell elhitetni a tudatlan magyar allampolgarral, hogy az integracio ertelme nem is lehet mas, mint Magyarorszagnak az altaluk propagalt EU-tagsaga. Ergo: aki egyeztert azzal, hogy szukseges es kivanatos Magyarorszag integracioja Nyugat-Europa iranyaban, az gyakorlatilag azt is elismeri, hogy Magyarorszagnak szukseges csatlakoznia az Europai Uniohoz.ITT VAN A FELREVEZETES LENYEGE!Konnyu belatni, hogy bar az Europai Unio valoban egy integracios folyamat termeke, de az Europai Unio mellett es azonkivul sok egyeb integracios folyamat is letezik. Roviden: AZ EUROPAI UNIO CSAK EGYIKE A SOK EGYEB INTEGRACIOS FOLYAMATNAK, es valaki teljes erovel tamogathatja Magyarorszag nyugat-europai torekveseit szamos integracios teruleten, mikozben hatarozottan ellenzi az orszag tagsagat az Eurooai Unioban. Azaz MAGYARORSZAGON LEHET VALAKI AZ INTEGRACIO HIVE, MIKOZBEN ELLENE VAN AZ EU-BA VALO BELEPESNEK.Ezert teljesen hamis az a liberalis beallitas, hogy aki az Europai Unio ellen van, az az integracio ellen is van. Termeszetesen kozismert jelenseg a gazdasagi-muszaki tevekenyseg egyre novekvo osszefonodasa, ezt mindenki jol latja, es az ebbol eredo integracio sok specifikus esetben indokolt lehet, de ez meg egyaltalan nem jelenti azt, hogy emiatt szukseges Magyarorszag tagsaga az EU-ban. Roviden: INTEGRACIO SZELEKTIV ALAPON IGEN, EUROPAI UNIO NEM.MILYEN INTEGRACIO?Minthogy az integracio csatlakozast jelent valamifele, egy mar meglevo gazdasagi, muszaki vagy akar tarsadalmi-politikai rendszerhez, akar orszagosan, akar az elet egy szukebb teruleten, ezert mindenfajta ilyen integracionak elofeltetele, hogy az valamifele REALIS ELONYT JELENTSEN MAGYAR SZEMPONTBOL. Elonyos lehet peldaul, ha csatlakozunk bizonyos kornyezetvedelmi megallapodasokhoz, mert igy talan nagyobb az esely a fektelen magyarorszagi kornyezetszennyezes visszaszoritasara, vagy netan a Szlovakiabol erkezo ipari szenny megfekezesere -- felteve persze, hogy az egyezmenyek betarthatok es kikenyszerithetok. Minthogy Magyraorszagnak kulcshelyzete van Kozep-Europaban, igy a telekkomunikacios vagy kozlekedestechnikai integraciobol is lehetnek elonyeink, persze csak akkor, ha a magyar fel azokat felismeri es az integracios egyuttmukodesben ervenyre is juttatja.A fentiekbol is lathato, hogy teljesen hamis es felrevezeto az integraciorol csak ugy altalanossagban beszelni. A varhato elonyoket es esetleges hatranyokat minden esetben konkretan meg kell vizsgalni, es csak igy lehet megitelni, hogy az adott esetben az integracio elonyos-e Magyarorszagnak vagy sem. Nincs integracio csak ugy altalaban!INTEGRACIO VAGY KISEMMIZESAz integracio emlegetese kulonosen felhaborito, amikor az orszagot manipulalo LIBERALIS-MAGYARELLENES KLIKK AZ ORSZAG KISEMMIZESET INTEGRACIONAK IGYEKSZIK FELTUNTETNI. Gondoljunk itt a magyar nemzeti vagyon atjatszasara idegen kezekbe. A liberalisok a kulfoldi vallalatokat diszkreten multinacionalis cegeknek titulaljak, pedig ezeknel csak a profitot termelo munkastomeg "multinacionalis", a toke haszna nagyon is "nacionalis", "nemzeti" tuajdonosok kezere vandorol: New Yorkba, Frankfurtba, Parizsba, Londonba es mas nyugati penzkozpontokba.A nagy nyugati monopolcegek behatolasa a magyar gazdasagba -- a magyar vallalatok felszippantasa reven -- nem integracio, hanem GAZDASAGI INVAZIO MAGYARORSZAG ELLEN, az orszag gazdasagi megszallasa. Az integracio feltetelezi, hogy az elonyos minden resztvevonek, a kolcsonos erdekegyeztetes alapjan. Minthogy a kulfoldi cegek magyarorszagi behatolasa -- nehany ritka kiveteltol eltekintve -- a magyar munkasok, a magyar termelok es altalaban a magyar lakossag karara tortent, ezert az nem integracio, hanem legalizalt fosztogatas, Maygarorszag kisemmizese.Nem lehet szotlanul turni, hogy a liberalis kozgazdasz "szakertok" es a fizetett kormanypropagandistak tovabb amitsak a magyar kozvelemenyt az integracio hamis mitoszaval. Egyebkent is, Magyarorszagot nem kell az integraciora, azaz az egyuttmukodesre tanitani. Maygarorszag mar regota egyuttmukodott a vilaggal, amikor az integracio kifejezest neg fel sem talaltak, bizonyitja ezt az orszag es a kulonfele szakintezmenyek tagsaga nemzetkozi szervezetekben mar az evszazad kezdete ota! Igy tekintve Magyarorszag europai es nemzetkozi integracioja immar evszazados folyamat.Akik most Magyarorszag kulfoldi gazdasagi megszallasat integracionak igyekeznek beallitani, azok vagy hihetetlenul tudatlanok, vagy pedig a kulfoldi penzuralom cinikus kiszolgaloi.ELSODLEGES: A NEMEZTI OSSZERDEKA modern technika es a sokoldalu gazdasagi-kereskedelmi kapcsolatok korszakaban senki se vitathatja, hogy a nemzetkozi egyuttmukodes bovulese vilagjelenseg, es ez Magyarorszagra is revenyes. A kerdes tehat nem az, hogy bovuljon-e az egyuttmukodes, hanem az, hogy milyen legyen es kinek legyen elonyos. Ez a kulcskerdes. Meg vilagosabban: tamogatni kell minden olyan egyuttmukodest (integraciot), amely elosegiti a magyar nep gazdasagi felemelkedeset, es segiti altalanos nemzeti torekveseink megvalosulasat, de EL KELL UTASITANI MINDEN OLYAN EGYUTTMoKODESI KISERLETET, AMI BARMI MODON IS SERTI A MAGYAR NEP ERDEKEIT, akar kozvetlenul, akar kozvetve.A nagyobb allamok ujabban eppen a nemzetkozi szervezetek manupulacioja reven igyekeznek befolyast szerezni a kisebb allamokban, hogy azutan azokat teljesen alarendeljek sajat erdekeiknek. Ez huzodik meg az Europai Unio es a NATO tervezett "kibovitese" mogott is.Ilyen helyzetben a kis allamok nepeinek elsorendu, eletbevagoan fontos erdeke, hogy olyan kormanyuk legyen, amely kulso erok reszerol nem kenyszeritheto es nem zsarolhato, azaz nem manipulalhato az orszag sajat nepe ellen. Magyarorszagon meg sokat kell tenni annak erdekeben, hogy a valasztopolgarok felfogjak enne a jelentoseget es a valasztasokon ennek megfeleloen szavazzanak.Dr. Plenter Janos==OMRI RUSSIAN PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION SURVEY No. 7, 7 JUNE 1996ZHIRINOVSKY APPEALS TO ETHNIC RUSSIANS. Wearing the bright red jacket that has become a trademark of his presidential campaign, Vladimir Zhirinovsky promised to end policies being carried out "at the expense of the Russian people" during his five-minute Russian Public TV (ORT) appearance on 5 June. Zhirinovsky asserted that the ethnically-defined regions of the Russian Federation, such as the republics of Tatarstan, Yakutiya, and the northern Caucasus, pay less in taxes yet receive more money from the federal budget than other regions. He added, "Today, we Russians live worse, are poorer, and we die sooner. We have fewer rights. The majority of children at train stations are--who? Russians. The majority of girls walking the streets in Europe are--who? Russians. The majority of dead soldiers are--who? Russians. The majority of scientists who have left--Russians. The majority of teachers and doctors who aren't paid their salaries--just the same, it's primarily in the [ethnic] Russian regions. It's a war against the Russian people." Zhirinovsky has been known to speak in an emotional style, but lately he has tried to foster a more statesmanlike image, and he delivered this monologue in a calm voice. He mentioned that in recent days he has tried to reach a political compromise with both the incumbent and the Communists. In closing, Zhirinovsky asked voters not to believe what he called false information published in newspapers about the electoral prospects of various candidates. Recent opinion polls suggest that Zhirinovsky will finish at best a distant third in the first round, but polls have traditionally understated support for Zhirinovsky. -- Laura BelinGORBACHEV AD STRESSES AN ALTERNATIVE TO YELTSIN, ZYUGANOV. In his political advertisements broadcast on 30 May, former USSR President Mikhail Gorbachev asserted that two-thirds of the electorate does not want to vote for either Yeltsin or Zyuganov but will end up choosing between "bad and worse" because they believe that they are the only realistic candidates. Although Gorbachev criticized both of the front runners, his main target was Yeltsin, the man responsible for removing him from power. He faulted Yeltsin's government for destroying half of the country's economic potential, forcing the majority of citizens into poverty, and taking away individuals' sense of security. Gorbachev argued that Yeltsin answered the people's faith in him with the Belavezha accord, shock therapy, launching an attack on the parliament, and Chechnya. He questioned the reasonableness of the people surrounding Zyuganov and noted that the choice between the two is only dividing society. He then argued that the salvation of Russia is neither in "Mafia capital" nor "a new communist experiment." Having rejected the alternative, he presented a bland program of supporting Russia's poorest citizens, stopping the bloodshed, fighting crime, rooting out corruption, improving access to health care, and restoring the strength of the military. He said that he would do many things differently now if he had the chance, but that his overall goals remain the same: "give people their freedom, make them masters of their fate, and help the especially needy." He called on his viewers to "vote by your conscience." Several slides at the end of the clip show him while he was still general secretary listening to speakers in a crowd on the street and to Yeltsin giving a speech. The last slides show him campaigning, signing autographs, and receiving flowers. -- Robert OrttungCAMPAIGNS CHARGE EACH OTHER WITH VIOLATIONS. Vyacheslav Volkov, Yeltsin's representative at the Central Electoral Commission, and Duma deputy Vladimir Ryzhkov charged the Communists with numerous campaign law violations on 6 June, Russian Public TV (ORT) reported. They accused Zyuganov supporters of using Duma offices and telephones for campaign purposes, organizing strike committees with Duma resources, issuing flyers that insult the president and stir up social, national, and religious hatreds, frightening rural residents, and calling for the use of illegal means to overthrow the present regime. They claimed Yeltsin's campaign is also guilty of some violations, but that these were quickly corrected and were not so widespread as the Communist transgressions. At the same time, Duma Defense Committee Chairman Viktor Ilyukhin asked the Procurator General's Office to investigate the executive branch for using its resources to support the Yeltsin campaign, NTV reported. Democratic Party of Russia leader Sergei Glazev, who is backing Aleksandr Lebed, charged that former Deputy Prime Minister Anatolii Chubais is involved in "racketeering and banditism" in getting money from commercial banks although he refused to give any specific examples, Ekho Moskvy reported. -- Robert OrttungZYUGANOV STRESSES MASS APPEAL. A 10-minute campaign video for Gennadii Zyuganov aired on Russian Public TV (ORT) on 3 June, using footage from numerous pro-Communist campaign rallies to emphasize Zyuganov's mass appeal. (From 4 to 14 June, the candidates receive free air time in 5- minute blocks.) The opening montage shows a map of the Soviet Union breaking up into 15 separate countries, superimposed over a burning field. Then Zyuganov is shown with crowds of supporters, patriotic music is played, and the pieces of the map come back together to form one unit, over which Zyuganov's slogan--"Russia, Motherland, [the] People"-- is superimposed. During the next two and a half minutes, several prominent figures give testimonials in favor of Zyuganov, including Duma Security Committee Chairman Viktor Ilyukhin and the actress Lyudmila Zaitseva (she is Zyuganov's campaign aide and played the mother in the film Little Vera). The rest of the video is devoted to scenes from Zyuganov rallies and speeches. Addressing thousands of supporters at the war memorial in Volgograd, Zyuganov says:We came here today not only to bow our heads in memory of those who perished, not only to recall their courage and will but also to say out loud, to our country, to our people, to our superpower (derzhava), that we will be true to the best heroic and labor traditions of our people, and we will do everything we can to restore to the people our Fatherland. (cheers from crowd).The next segment shows Zyuganov speaking to a packed hall in an unidentified city. As he speaks, members of the audience--most of them young--are on camera much of the time. (This is presumably to counter the widespread belief that Zyuganov appeals mainly to pensioners.) The candidate says:What do we propose to correct the situation? First, we need to change course. Any state ship should know where it is sailing. This course should be the clear and well-defined goal of [the state's] existence. The first goal should be the well-being of the citizens and stopping the death of the country. Until this problem is solved, other tasks don't make any sense. In order to solve this problem, we need to clearly envision what the economy should be like and support producers. The country should have a powerful state sector, which would allow us to teach children, provide [medical] treatment for the elderly, support state institutions, and provide for the security of citizens and the normal functioning of all basic institutions.In this connection, we must clearly define the priorities of this economy. Without power engineering, you won't get anything from a power engineering specialist. [Other priorities are] high technology, science, quality education available to all, and accessible medical services. This does not mean that there should not be other forms [of ownership]. There should be. But they should supplement, and not destroy, what was created at workplaces. Proportions between state collectives and private forms of property should enable them to compete, not to suppress, but to supplement each other.On our territory, the state should regulate the two most important indexes: prices for oil and gas, and prices for transportation expenses and tariffs. Otherwise, you wouldn't be able to compete with anyone.We are extremely interested in having money sitting in Western banks returned to Russia, to work for our science, for constructing roads, for introducing new technology, and for great discoveries. For this reason, we are considering adopting a law that would facilitate the return of capital and its investment in the Russian economy on fixed, fully acceptable terms ...As concerns joint ventures and various forms of property, it is clearly written in our program: we will support all who know how to work competently and normally. We will create a guarantee for this in law.The video then shows more crowd scenes and Zyuganov shaking hands with supporters. He addresses a different audience with these words:Gorbachev's five-year plan led us to a situation in which the country required humanitarian aid. Yeltsin's five-year plans ended in the devastation of the economy, war in Chechnya, and the decimation of the Russian population. If we continue this policy for two or three more years, we will lose not just a collective or state farm, not just a factory or an enterprise. We will lose the patriotic country that was created by our ancestors over the course of a thousand years. [Our ancestors] defended it, guarded it, and they will curse us for allowing such a thing to happen.On the other hand, no matter who comes to power tomorrow, it will not be a piece of cake for him. Who says we will win the election? There may be no victories in your fatherland. No one has ever yet secured victory over his own people. Whoever comes to power, ... his team will have to eliminate the most difficult consequences [of the current policy], it will have to display wisdom, courage and restraint, and carry out a policy in the interests of all social layers of the population.You suggest that I pound my fist. I would rather have strong nerves, courage, a clear head, political will, [and] awareness of what is going on. And then we will surely show them their place. (applause).The video ends with more scenes of massive pro-Zyuganov rallies and marches, hands grabbing for pro-Zyuganov leaflets--all accompanied by triumphant music. News programs of major television networks often show pro-Yeltsin rallies, but footage of huge crowds in support of Zyuganov are rarely seen. -- Translated by Laura Belin and Anna ParetskayaMEDIANE DAI BOG! SEEKS TO STIR UP ANTI-COMMUNIST SENTIMENT. Ne dai bog! is the reformers' answer to such radical anti-Yeltsin newspapers as Zavtra. It has a circulation of 10 million copies and is distributed free in mailboxes across the country. It was initially faulted for not publishing the members of its editorial board and print run but quickly corrected those problems to bring itself in line with the law. According to a letter from the editorial board in issue no. 4 (11 May) the paper does not like Gennadii Zyuganov, however it does not explicitly support Yeltsin, saying only that it supports "counting on yourself, on your own freedom to build your life." The editorial board, however, refuses to reveal who finances the colorful paper that contains no advertisements. The newspaper only says that it receives funding from "a group of well- off Russian citizens who are very concerned about what happens with this country after 16 June." The articles sharply attack Zyuganov. One piece in issue no. 5 (18 May) argues that the author of Zyuganov's platform "Russia. Motherland. People." "used the ideology, psychological methods, and textual constructions favored by Adolf Hitler during the late 1920s and early 1930s." An article in issue no. 3 (5 April) asks radical anti- communist Democratic Union leader Valeriya Novodvorskaya to imagine what she would do if she were Zyuganov. Novodvorskaya imagines Zyuganov as a spider who "comes slowly to his victim, and waits while he entangles himself and stops moving, so it is possible to quietly suck his blood." Novodvorskaya, often charged with insulting the president and most recently with maligning the entire Russian people, concludes that if she were Zyuganov, the best thing to do would be to hang herself. Issue no. 3 also contains a report from the extremist Russian Communist Workers' Party congress in Chelyabinsk 20-21 April in which the party "discussed preparations to conduct military actions on Russian territory." Some suggest that the paper's over-the-top, slick anti-communism may offend readers and turn some voters away from Yeltsin. -- Robert OrttungANALYSIS AND PREDICTIONSSOCIOLOGISTS: ELECTION RESULTS MAY DIFFER FROM POLLS. The vice president of Boris Grushin's Vox Populi polling agency, Aleksandr Kinsburgskii, said that the results of the 16 June presidential election may differ considerably from current public opinion polls, ITAR-TASS reported on 4 June. He argued that direct rating indicators, such as popularity polls, greatly contradict indirect indicators, such as questions on particular issues, since the former are highly influenced by the mass media. Moreover, a large proportion of the respondents hide their actual affiliations when polled. In the 1993 and 1995 parliamentary election, opinion poll surveys and predictions were highly unreliable. Under Russian law, 12 June is the last day for releasing the results of opinion polls and research related to the presidential race. -- Anna ParetskayaEXPERT EVALUATES CAMPAIGN STRATEGIES OF YAVLINSKII, ZHIRINOVSKY. Grigorii Yavlinskii's presidential campaign is "extremely poor and extremely unprofessional," practically a model of how not to run for president, according to Sergei Markov, program associate at the Carnegie Moscow Center. Speaking at the center on 6 June, Markov noted the poor quality of Yavlinskii's leaflets and advertisements. In contrast, he argued, Vladimir Zhirinovsky understands that this year is not "his time." Instead, he is consolidating his own position by targeting his own electorate with effective advertisements and speeches. Markov expressed the view--widely held in Moscow--that Zhirinovsky sometimes works in tandem with the government. By way of example, he noted that the media prominently covered Zhirinovsky's recent accusations that Gennadii Zyuganov and Yavlinskii were planning to join forces. However, the media did not carry the two candidates' denials of this charge. Markov concluded that the government may have told Zhirinovsky to make this accusation to discredit Zyuganov and Yavlinskii among their supporters. -- Laura Belin in MoscowThis material was reprinted with permission of the Open Media       Research Institute, a nonprofit organization with research offices in       Prague, Czech Republic. For more information on OMRI publications,       please write to:  info@omri.cz
